</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ECB67C746EFC1705133C2BF652C54F63" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A12EF52BC9E0B2451192102744BAF2FE" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8297F3F24C3B66BAC3FE40116099BAE6" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">OL:OH = 0.85-0.92. Ventral rim deeply curving, deepest anterior of its middle. Anterior rim slightly inclined, almost straight from broad, inferior rostrum to predorsal angle with minute excisura and antirostrum. Inner face flat, outer face convex, smooth. OCL:CCL = 1.2-1.5.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="116639EC4C716D28ADF3A725C2442923" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="description">
<paragraph id="543603DFB7688EED7D5E6AB43304F61E" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA8E8847693D8BAF643FB5F86570D5E5" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">A small, very high-bodied, robust and thick otolith reaching about 1.5 mm in length (holotype); OH:OT = 3.4-3.7. Ventral rim deeply curving, deepest anterior of its middle, curving backwards into a steeply rounded posterior rim. Dorsal rim relatively shallow and nearly flat with distinct postdorsal angle at junction with posterior rim, somewhat irregular. Anterior rim steeply inclined at 75-85° (with sulcus oriented horizontal), nearly straight from distinct, rounded and inferior rostrum to minute antirostrum and predorsal angle at junction with anterior rim. Excisura minute. All rims smooth.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FAD4AA9C198AC84BCA6EED9BF76853E6" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Inner face completely flat, with long, relatively wide, straight, shallow and slightly supramedian positioned sulcus. Ostial colliculum shallow, slightly longer and distinctly wider than caudal colliculum (OCL:CCL = 1.2-1.5; OCH:CCH = 1.25-1.5). Caudal pseudocolliculum as long as caudal colliculum. Ventral furrow distinct, positioned far from ventral rim of otolith. Dorsal depression wide, occupying almost entire dorsal field, but with indistinct margins. Outer face distinctly convex, smooth.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FBB7C64CB10DC0195617C791C8C683B" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="868BC9191DC66F1E651413CCF6DAEBF5" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0516D603F99E44AE2E62A8FCEE599C03" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="5975F98AD5656480FC122EF1F73A890B" authorityName="Schwarzhans &amp; Ohe &amp; Tsuchiya &amp; Ujihara" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Lampanyctus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lampanyctus tsuyamaensis" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tsuyamaensis">
<emphasis id="CB43B385C78436EC8C72B3B0CBFEEC91" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Lampanyctus tsuyamaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="7C4AEB465CFA39E6FCFFB15869440486" genus="L." lsidName="L. popoto" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="popoto">
<emphasis id="7D22375D292A4B0F70009B8DC15640B6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. popoto</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schwarzhans, 2019 from the early Miocene of New Zealand and 
<taxonomicName id="B10EFD1FAE62CDA0175F8E24B318D0F1" genus="L." lsidName="L. latesulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="latesulcatus">
<emphasis id="5574719E210CA92B81101E7D6B442D45" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. latesulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Nolf &amp; Steurbaut, 1983 from the late Miocene of Italy but can be readily distinguished from both species by the more high-bodied shape, which is also expressed in the OL:OH ratio of 0.85-0.92 (vs. 0.95-1.05 and&gt; 1.0, respectively). Another distinctive character is the straight, inclined anterior rim and the asymmetrical ventral rim. The known otoliths of extant species of 
<taxonomicName id="38215829F34C2983E8C8808B9748DE45" authorityName="Bonaparte in Bonaparte" authorityYear="1840" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Lampanyctus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lampanyctus" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1434383D541D9DB7AA7836ADE3D9CA74" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Lampanyctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually also less high-bodied, with the exceptions of 
<taxonomicName id="D896445C0974E22E63C241019DD43EE0" genus="L." lsidName="L. lepidolychnus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lepidolychnus">
<emphasis id="5E6C326F713B7E62CBA4C8E7AA528ECD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. lepidolychnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Becker, 1967 and 
<taxonomicName id="AA3ABBFBB71B0B13540C2FE5B407CBAD" genus="L." lsidName="L. macdonaldi" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="macdonaldi">
<emphasis id="CB5D215053878AFBB2AC9B56F81ECD17" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. macdonaldi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Goode &amp; Bean, 1896). Otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="276A7CACBBD61EF069DB8F1A35C591AB" genus="L." lsidName="L. lepidolychnus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lepidolychnus">
<emphasis id="7EB16495167D60B068C5C059C517338D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. lepidolychnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="8CBA464A68607685E580C5A2CF351F98" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" author="Smale, MJ" journalOrPublisher="Smith Institute of Ichthyology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 253" refId="B71" refString="Smale, MJ, Watson, G, Hecht, T, 1995. Otolith atlas of South African marine fishes. Ichthyological Monographs of the J.L.B. Smith Institute of Ichthyology 1: 1 - 253, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" title="Otolith atlas of South African marine fishes. Ichthyological Monographs of the J. L. B." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" volume="1" year="1995">Smale et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
for figures) differ in the less inclined anterior rim, a more distinct development of a broad excisura, and a more regularly rounded dorsal rim, while those of 
<taxonomicName id="2AE47175BC05B87B6477FC8B1708E975" genus="L." lsidName="L. macdonaldi" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="macdonaldi">
<emphasis id="D856A741C5F0D65BE7FBD890F0458F76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. macdonaldi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are among the very few myctophid otoliths with fused colliculi (note that the specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="6B9BCF7AE2A203666449763EB4DE3F90" genus="L." lsidName="L. macdonaldi" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="macdonaldi">
<emphasis id="A749EC84670304F4E7569A3235175899" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. macdonaldi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
figured in 
<bibRefCitation id="FDE51AE554C1AB6BCDCEECBB1D8105AF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" author="Smale, MJ" journalOrPublisher="Smith Institute of Ichthyology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="1 - 253" refId="B71" refString="Smale, MJ, Watson, G, Hecht, T, 1995. Otolith atlas of South African marine fishes. Ichthyological Monographs of the J.L.B. Smith Institute of Ichthyology 1: 1 - 253, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" title="Otolith atlas of South African marine fishes. Ichthyological Monographs of the J. L. B." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.141860" volume="1" year="1995">Smale et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
are erroneously identified). In contrast, the otoliths of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="BDE1BEF718D086819A6C491935AFE30C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Nannobrachium" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nannobrachium" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="209814E271F97EB555C48275D48EF5BE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Nannobrachium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="26ABB36D26813EE06532B7C0B5F671F5" originalValue="Günther">Guenther</normalizedToken>
, 1887, which is commonly synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="B093FC241C753263E9D3039BFE399EA4" authorityName="Bonaparte in Bonaparte" authorityYear="1840" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Lampanyctus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lampanyctus" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="075E6D2AD6C232813A18BB87CAF6DD86" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Lampanyctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are even more compressed and high-bodied with a near rectangular outline and the sulcus almost reaching the posterior rim of the otolith.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
